  "report": {
    "narrative": [
      "The hottest GPUs observed in the 2026-03-01..2026-03-24 historical window are concentrated on host family k002-004-v* (all on GPU card 0) with a peak temperature of 82°C, followed by several GPUs on k002-003 in the low 70s °C. Based on the preview data, temperature is the only GPU-stress dimension available; there are no accompanying GPU utilization, VRAM pressure, power, throttling, XGMI error, or ECC-like fault metrics shown, so correlation to “GPU activity” is not possible from this extract.\n\nTop thermal hotspots (highest priority to investigate):\n- k002-004-v5:8000 card0 at 82°C\n- k002-004-v7:8000 card0 at 81°C\n- k002-004-v1:8000 card0 at 79°C\nNext tier:\n- k002-004-v8:8000 card0 at 76°C\n- k002-004-v6:8000 card0 at 75°C\nLower tier in this sample:\n- k002-003:8000 card4 at 72°C; card2 at 71°C; card6 at 69°C\n\nHost context / pattern: the fact that multiple separate hosts in the k002-004-v* group appear at the top (and all on card 0) suggests either (a) repeated workload placement that heavily uses GPU0, (b) a systematic cooling/airflow or fan-curve issue affecting those nodes similarly, or (c) instrumentation bias (only certain GPUs/hosts reported). Without per-GPU utilization/power and per-host thermal telemetry (inlet temp, fan RPM, throttling flags), this remains ambiguous.\n\nWhat to check first (actionable triage order):\n1) k002-004-v5 card0, then k002-004-v7 card0: verify whether temperatures are sustained (vs brief spikes), and whether throttling occurred.\n2) k002-004-v1 card0: compare against other cards on the same node (not shown here) to detect a single-GPU cooling anomaly.\n3) k002-003 cards 4/2/6: lower urgency, but useful as a comparator node for “normal under load” temperatures in the same window.\n\nConfidence: high that these are the hottest GPUs present in the preview results; low on “most stressed” overall because utilization/VRAM/power/error signals are missing in the provided dataset preview."
    ],
